✅ 1. Change Target at Runtime (Temporary)
👉 This change is ONLY for current session (no reboot persistence)
Use:
systemctl isolate multi-user.target
OR
systemctl isolate graphical.target

✅ What happens

Immediately switches system state
Stops services not part of target
Starts required services for target


✅ Example
Switch GUI → CLI:
systemctl isolate multi-user.target
Switch CLI → GUI:
systemctl isolate graphical.target

✅ Interview one-liner
isolate = runtime target switch (temporary, immediate)

✅ 2. Change Target Permanently (Default Boot Target)
👉 This change applies after reboot
Use:
systemctl set-default multi-user.target
OR
systemctl set-default graphical.target

✅ Example
Set CLI mode permanently:
systemctl set-default multi-user.target
Set GUI permanently:
systemctl set-default graphical.target

✅ Check current default
systemctl get-default

✅ What it does internally
Creates symlink:
/etc/systemd/system/default.target → chosen target

✅ 3. Combined Usage (Real Scenario)
👉 You want immediate + permanent change:
Step 1 (runtime):
systemctl isolate multi-user.target
Step 2 (permanent):
systemctl set-default multi-user.target

✅ 4. Targets Quick Reference
multi-user.target → CLI mode (no GUI)
graphical.target → GUI mode
rescue.target → single-user (troubleshooting)
emergency.target → minimal shell

✅ 5. Troubleshooting Tip
If GUI not working:
systemctl isolate multi-user.target
Fix issue →
systemctl isolate graphical.target

✅ 6. Quick Difference (Important)
isolate:

Immediate
Temporary
No reboot needed

set-default:

Permanent
Applies after reboot
Safe for production change

